rse primary sources, van Deusen shows that these women recognized the divine-or were objectified as conduits of holiness-in innovative and powerful ways: dressing a religious statue, performing charitable acts, sharing interiorized spiritual visions, constructing autobiographical texts, or offering their hair or fingernails to disciples as living relics. In these manifestations of piety, each of these women transcended the limited outlets available to them for expressing and enacting their faith in colonial Lima, and each transformed early modern Catholicism in meaningful ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aMysticismxHistoryx17th centuryxPeruxLima. 0aMysticismzPeruzLimaxHistoryy17th century. 0aMysticism. 0aWomen mysticsxHistoryx17th centuryxPeruxLima. 0aWomen mysticsxPeruxLima. 0aWomen mysticszPeruzLimaxHistoryy17th century. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2018z978311069633240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822372288423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822372288.jpg  a978-3-11-069633-2  DUK eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles